04031nam a22005535i 9780226734897DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20072001ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267348977 a10.7208/97802267348972doi  a(DE-B1597)524347  a(OCoLC)781254908  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF175.4.R44 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a200.19a200/.1/9a200/.1/91 aSantner, Eric L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Psychotheology of Everyday Life :bReflections on Freud and Rosenzweig /cEric L. Santner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. In the Midst of Life -- tCHAPTER TWO. From the Reign of the Undead to the Blessings of More Life -- tCHAPTER THREE. Toward an Ethics of Singularity -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Responsibility beyond the Superego -- tEpilogue: What Remains -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn On the Psychotheology of Everyday Life, Eric Santner puts Sigmund Freud in dialogue with his contemporary Franz Rosenzweig in the service of reimagining ethical and political life. By exploring the theological dimensions of Freud's writings and revealing unexpected psychoanalytic implications in the religious philosophy of Rosenzweig's masterwork, The Star of Redemption, Santner makes an original argument for understanding religions of revelation in therapeutic terms, and offers a penetrating look at how this understanding suggests fruitful ways of reconceiving political community. Santner's crucial innovation in this new study is to bring the theological notion of revelation into a broadly psychoanalytic field, where it can be understood as a force that opens the self to everyday life and encourages accountability within the larger world. Revelation itself becomes redefined as an openness toward what is singular, enigmatic, even uncanny about the Other, whether neighbor or stranger, thereby linking a theory of drives and desire to a critical account of sociality. Santner illuminates what it means to be genuinely open to another human being or culture and to share and take responsibility for one's implication in the dilemmas of difference. By bringing Freud and Rosenzweig together, Santner not only clarifies in new and surprising ways the profound connections between psychoanalysis and the Judeo-Christian tradition, he makes the resources of both available to contemporary efforts to rethink concepts of community and cross-cultural communication.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPsychoanalysis and philosophy. 0aPsychoanalysis and religion. 0aPsychology and philosophy. 0aPsychology and religion. 0aPsychology. 0aReligion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226734897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226734897.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles